stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":6,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":3597,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":22336,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":3597,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ1PQ8gcRByH3LWoQ7QbF\",\"uuid\":\"48deb40f-cbac-4869-9b63-878530f41da3\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"aed8a7a9a168c4993\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01BtxMUFHXNLVfLC41bjHuef\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01B6waxy48tcKtxdjkY1zHUg\",\"uuid\":\"289dbaea-43d2-4b9b-8066-ce34d31e74ee\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-13T16:22:26.835Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/ninawork/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"f01db921-a255-4978-9c64-3a353600bda3\",\"version\":\"2.1.74\",\"gitBranch\":\"attach-session-id\",\"slug\":\"tingly-herding-sutton\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"289dbaea-43d2-4b9b-8066-ce34d31e74ee\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01ENApJbq8pyedKqe8UyhtTN\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Checkpoint Sync Architecture\\n     2→\\n     3→Checkpoints are snapshots of AI coding sessions created by the Entire CLI. This document covers how checkpoint data flows through the system.\\n     4→\\n     5→See [Data Sync Architecture](./data-sync-architecture.md) for the overall system architecture.\\n     6→\\n     7→## Architecture: Repo-Centric Storage\\n     8→\\n     9→Checkpoint data is stored at the **repo level**, not per-user. This eliminates redundant API calls when multiple users have access to the same repository.\\n    10→\\n    11→```\\n    12→repos (global, one per GitHub repo)\\n    13→  ├── app_has_access (GitHub App installed?)\\n    14→  ├── checkpoints_backfilled_at\\n    15→  ├── checkpoints_last_synced_at\\n    16→  └── repo_checkpoints / repo_checkpoint_commits (shared across users)\\n    17→\\n    18→users\\n    19→  ├── repos_synced_at (when we last refreshed their repo list)\\n    20→  └── user_repos (join table) → repos\\n    21→```\\n    22→\\n    23→**Benefit:** 3 users with access to `acme/app` = 1 checkpoint sync, shared data.\\n    24→\\n    25→## OAuth vs GitHub App Installation\\n    26→\\n    27→Understanding the two types of GitHub access is critical:\\n    28→\\n    29→| Access Type | What It Provides | Limitations |\\n    30→|-------------|------------------|-------------|\\n    31→| **User OAuth Token** | List of repos the user can access | Cannot read repo contents |\\n    32→| **GitHub App Installation** | Read access to repo contents | Only for repos where app is installed |\\n    33→\\n    34→```\\n    35→User logs in (OAuth) → \\\"Here are your 1000 repos\\\" (list only)\\n    36→GitHub App installed  → \\\"I can read checkpoint data from these 50 repos\\\"\\n    37→```\\n    38→\\n    39→The `repos.app_has_access` flag is set by **installation webhooks**, not by user login. Users see their full repo list immediately, but checkpoint data only appears for repos where the GitHub App is installed.\\n    40→\\n    41→## Prerequisites: Repository Sync\\n    42→\\n    43→Checkpoints are tied to repositories. Before checkpoint sync can occur:\\n    44→\\n    45→1. **Repository must exist in D1** - User's repos are synced via `POST /repos/sync` (see data-sync-architecture.md)\\n    46→2. **GitHub App must have access** - Tracked in `repos.app_has_access` (updated via installation webhooks)\\n    47→3. **entire/sessions branch must exist** - The Entire CLI creates this branch when saving checkpoints\\n    48→\\n    49→**Repository table fields used by checkpoint sync:**\\n    50→```sql\\n    51→repos.id                          -- Foreign key for checkpoints\\n    52→repos.full_name                   -- Used for GitHub API calls\\n    53→repos.app_has_access              -- Skip repos where App isn't installed\\n    54→repos.checkpoints_backfilled_at   -- NULL = needs initial sync, set after backfill\\n    55→repos.checkpoints_last_synced_at  -- Last successful sync timestamp\\n    56→```\\n    57→\\n    58→## Data Model\\n    59→\\n    60→```\\n    61→┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\n    62→│                         entire/sessions branch                          │\\n    63→│                      (pushed by Entire CLI)                             │\\n    64→├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\\n    65→│  ab/cdef123456/                                                         │\\n    66→│  ├── metadata.json    ──► repo_checkpoints table (session metadata)     │\\n    67→│  ├── prompt.txt       ──► repo_checkpoints.prompt (first line)          │\\n    68→│  └── transcript.json  ──► served on-demand via /transcript endpoint     │\\n    69→└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\\n    70→\\n    71→┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\n    72→│                         feature branches                                │\\n    73→│                      (main, feature-x, etc.)                            │\\n    74→├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\\n    75→│  Commits with \\\"Entire-Checkpoint: <id>\\\" trailer                         │\\n    76→│  ──► repo_checkpoint_commits table (commit data, diff stats)            │\\n    77→└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\\n    78→```\\n    79→\\n    80→### Database Schema\\n    81→\\n    82→**repo_checkpoints** - One row per checkpoint (session metadata from entire/sessions)\\n    83→```sql\\n    84→checkpoint_id         -- \\\"a0faa4317e7d\\\" (unique per repo)\\n    85→repo_id, branch       -- Original branch where checkpoint was created\\n    86→prompt                -- First line of prompt.txt\\n    87→agent                 -- \\\"Claude Code\\\"\\n    88→steps, session_count  -- From metadata.json\\n    89→strategy              -- \\\"auto-commit\\\", \\\"manual-commit\\\", etc.\\n    90→created_at            -- From metadata.json\\n    91→\\n    92→-- Extended metadata (from metadata.json)\\n    93→session_id            -- Primary session ID\\n    94→files_touched         -- JSON array of modified files\\n    95→session_ids           -- JSON array of all contributing sessions\\n    96→transcript_uuid_at_start, transcript_lines_at_start, checkpoint_transcript_start\\n    97→\\n    98→-- Token usage metrics\\n    99→input_tokens, cache_creation_tokens, cache_read_tokens\\n   100→output_tokens, api_call_count\\n   101→```\\n   102→\\n   103→**repo_checkpoint_commits** - One row per checkpoint per branch (commit data)\\n   104→```sql\\n   105→checkpoint_id, branch      -- Composite: same checkpoint can exist on multiple branches\\n   106→commit_sha, commit_message, commit_author, commit_date\\n   107→commit_author_github_id    -- GitHub user ID of commit author\\n   108→additions, deletions, files_changed  -- Diff stats\\n   109→```\\n   110→\\n   111→**checkpoint_sync_state** - Tracks sync progress per repo/branch\\n   112→```sql\\n   113→repo_id, branch\\n   114→last_commit_date           -- High-water mark for incremental sync\\n   115→last_success_at, last_error, last_error_at\\n   116→total_checkpoints_synced\\n   117→```\\n   118→\\n   119→## Sync Flow\\n   120→\\n   121→Checkpoints sync at the **repo level**, triggered by installation webhooks, user login, daily reconciliation, or on-demand. This is separate from user repo list sync.\\n   122→\\n   123→```\\n   124→┌────────────────────┐    ┌────────────────────┐    ┌────────────────────┐\\n   125→│  Installation      │    │    User Login      │    │  Daily Reconcile   │\\n   126→│  (app installed)   │    │  (missed webhook)  │    │   (3 AM UTC)       │\\n   127→└─────────┬──────────┘    └─────────┬──────────┘    └─────────┬──────────┘\\n   128→          │                         │                         │\\n   129→          └─────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┘\\n   130→                                    │\\n   131→                                    ▼\\n   132→                          ┌─────────────────┐\\n   133→                          │   D1 Database   │\\n   134→                          │  (repo-centric) │\\n   135→                          └─────────────────┘\\n   136→```\\n   137→\\n   138→### 1. Installation Webhook (App Access Granted)\\n   139→\\n   140→When the GitHub App is installed on a repo:\\n   141→\\n   142→```\\n   143→Webhook arrives → Upsert repos (set app_has_access = 1)\\n   144→               → Queue immediate checkpoint backfill (priority=10)\\n   145→               → Webhooks handle ongoing checkpoint updates\\n   146→```\\n   147→\\n   148→### 2. User Login (Missed Webhook Recovery)\\n   149→\\n   150→When a user logs in and their repos are synced, the system also queues checkpoint syncs for repos that:\\n   151→- Have `app_has_access = true` (GitHub App is installed)\\n   152→- Have `checkpoints_last_synced_at IS NULL` (never been synced)\\n   153→\\n   154→This handles the edge case where the GitHub App was installed before the backend started (or we missed the installation webhook). Without this, checkpoints wouldn't be fetched until the daily reconciliation at 3 AM UTC.\\n   155→\\n   156→```\\n   157→User logs in → syncReposForUser() runs\\n   158→            → Upsert repos (mark installation repos with app_has_access = true)\\n   159→            → Query repos needing checkpoint sync (app_has_access=1, never synced)\\n   160→            → Queue checkpoint backfill for each (priority=10)\\n   161→```\\n   162→\\n   163→### 3. Background Sync (Initial + Incremental)\\n   164→\\n   165→Processed by `repo-checkpoint-sync-queue` consumer. Runs at repo level, not user level.\\n   166→\\n   167→**Initial sync** runs for repos where `checkpoints_backfilled_at IS NULL`.\\n   168→**Incremental sync** runs for already-backfilled repos using `last_commit_date` from `checkpoint_sync_state` as a high-water mark.\\n   169→\\n   170→```\\n   171→Queue consumer → Process repo sync messages\\n   172→              → For each repo:\\n   173→                   1. Get token from any user with access to this repo\\n   174→                   2. Check entire/sessions branch exists\\n   175→                   3. Get last_commit_date from checkpoint_sync_state (if backfilled)\\n   176→                   4. Fetch commits from main branch (since last_commit_date for incremental)\\n   177→                   5. Parse Entire-Checkpoint trailers\\n   178→                   6. Batch fetch commit stats (GraphQL)\\n   179→                   7. Batch fetch session data from entire/sessions (GraphQL)\\n   180→                   8. Batch upsert to D1 (repo_checkpoints, repo_checkpoint_commits)\\n   181→                   9. Update checkpoint_sync_state.last_commit_date\\n   182→                  10. Mark repo as backfilled (initial sync only)\\n   183→              → Update repos.checkpoints_last_synced_at\\n   184→```\\n   185→\\n   186→**Token Fallback:** When fetching a token for repo sync, the system tries up to 5 users with access to the repo, ordered by token expiration (freshest first). If one user's token fails, the next is tried.\\n   187→\\n   188→### 4. Daily Reconciliation Cron\\n   189→\\n   190→```\\n   191→Cron (daily, 3 AM UTC) →\\n   192→  - Check rate limit state (skip if rate limited)\\n   193→  - Get repos where app_has_access=1 AND checkpoints_last_synced_at > 24h ago\\n   194→  - Queue for reconciliation (priority=1, batch of 50)\\n   195→```\\n   196→\\n   197→This ensures that even if webhooks are missed, the daily cron will catch up on any new commits (including merged PRs).\\n   198→\\n   199→### 5. Webhook Updates\\n   200→\\n   201→Two webhook handlers process checkpoint-related events:\\n   202→\\n   203→**Push to entire/sessions branch** → `processSessionsPushEvent()`\\n   204→```\\n   205→1. Parse added/modified files to extract checkpoint IDs\\n   206→2. Batch fetch session data (metadata.json, prompt.txt) via GraphQL\\n   207→3. Upsert to repo_checkpoints table\\n   208→```\\n   209→\\n   210→**Push to any other branch** → `processCommitPushEvent()`\\n   211→```\\n   212→1. Parse commits for Entire-Checkpoint trailer\\n   213→2. Batch fetch commit stats via GraphQL\\n   214→3. Upsert to repo_checkpoint_commits table\\n   215→```\\n   216→\\n   217→### 6. Data Serving\\n   218→\\n   219→```\\n   220→GET /api/v1/cache/:org/:repo/checkpoints?branch=main\\n   221→\\n   222→1. Query repo_checkpoints table joined with repo_checkpoint_commits\\n   223→2. Return CheckpointInfo[] (commit fields may be null if webhook hasn't arrived)\\n   224→```\\n   225→\\n   226→## GitHub API Efficiency\\n   227→\\n   228→All GitHub API calls use **batched GraphQL** to minimize requests:\\n   229→\\n   230→| Operation | API Calls | Notes |\\n   231→|-----------|-----------|-------|\\n   232→| Fetch commits from branch | 1 | Single REST call, 100 commits max |\\n   233→| Fetch commit stats | 1-2 | GraphQL batch, 50 commits per query |\\n   234→| Fetch session data | 1-5 | GraphQL batch, 20 checkpoints per query (2 files each) |\\n   235→\\n   236→For a repo with 100 checkpoints: **4-8 total API calls** (vs 200+ with REST).\\n   237→\\n   238→## Key Design Decisions\\n   239→\\n   240→1. **Repo-centric storage** - Checkpoint data is stored at the repo level (`repo_checkpoints`, `repo_checkpoint_commits`), not per-user. Multiple users with access to the same repo share the same checkpoint data, eliminating redundant API calls.\\n   241→\\n   242→2. **Branch stored in checkpoints table** - The `branch` field comes from `metadata.json`, not from checking which branches contain the commit. This allows querying checkpoints by branch without requiring commit data.\\n   243→\\n   244→3. **Nullable commit fields** - `CheckpointInfo` has nullable commit fields because the checkpoint data (from entire/sessions push) may arrive before the branch push webhook.\\n   245→\\n   246→4. **Separate queue for checkpoint sync** - Checkpoint sync runs in a dedicated `repo-checkpoint-sync-queue`, decoupled from user sync. This allows prioritization (installation webhooks get priority=10) and repo-level deduplication.\\n   247→\\n   248→5. **No on-demand GitHub fetches** - The `/checkpoints` endpoint only reads from D1. Background sync populates the data.\\n   249→\\n   250→6. **COALESCE on upsert** - New metadata fields use `COALESCE(excluded.field, repo_checkpoints.field)` to preserve existing values when incoming data is null.\\n   251→\\n   252→7. **Incremental sync with high-water mark** - The `checkpoint_sync_state` table tracks `last_commit_date` per repo/branch. Background sync uses this as a `since` parameter to GitHub's commits API, fetching only new commits. This catches missed webhooks (including merged PRs) without re-fetching the entire history.\\n   253→\\n   254→8. **Token fallback** - When syncing a repo, the system tries up to 5 users with access, ordered by token freshness. This improves reliability when individual tokens are expired or invalid.\\n   255→\\n   256→9. **Foreign-branch checkpoint filtering** - When processing push events for non-default branches, commits with `distinct: false` are filtered out. In GitHub push payloads, `distinct` indicates whether a given commit SHA has been seen before in this repository; once a commit has already been pushed (for example, via a merge from or direct push to another branch), subsequent push events will typically have `distinct: false` for that SHA. This keeps a branch's checkpoint list focused on commits that first appeared in that branch, instead of re-attributing work that originated elsewhere. The default branch is exempt from this filtering since it's the canonical integration point for all work.\\n   257→\\n   258→## Queue Configuration\\n   259→\\n   260→- Queue: `repo-checkpoint-sync-queue`\\n   261→- Consumer: `max_batch_size=5`, `max_retries=3`, `max_concurrency=2`\\n   262→- Cron trigger: `0 3 * * *` (3 AM UTC daily)\\n   263→\\n   264→### Priority Scheme\\n   265→\\n   266→| Trigger | Priority | Notes |\\n   267→|---------|----------|-------|\\n   268→| Installation webhook | 10 | Immediate backfill |\\n   269→| User login (missed webhook) | 10 | Immediate backfill for repos never synced |\\n   270→| Manual trigger | 5 | User-initiated sync |\\n   271→| Daily reconciliation | 1 | Low priority, batch of 50 |\\n   272→\\n   273→### Rate Limit Protection\\n   274→\\n   275→The system tracks GitHub API rate limit state in KV:\\n   276→- When a rate limit error is detected, a marker is set with the reset time\\n   277→- Cron and queue consumers check this marker before processing\\n   278→- If rate limited, cron skips entirely and queue messages are retried later\\n   279→- Marker auto-expires after 1 hour (self-cleaning)\\n   280→\\n   281→## Files\\n   282→\\n   283→| File | Purpose |\\n   284→|------|---------|\\n   285→| `src/lib/checkpoint-sync-service.ts` | Background sync logic (initial + incremental) |\\n   286→| `src/lib/github.ts` | `fetchSessionDataBatch()`, `fetchCommitStatsBatch()`, `fetchBranchCommitsForCheckpoints()` |\\n   287→| `src/lib/db.ts` | `upsertCheckpointBatch()`, `getCheckpointsForBranch()`, `getCheckpointSyncState()` |\\n   288→| `src/routes/webhooks.ts` | `processSessionsPushEvent()`, `processCommitPushEvent()` |\\n   289→| `src/routes/cache.ts` | `GET /checkpoints` endpoint |\\n   290→| `src/queues/checkpoint-sync-consumer.ts` | Process repo checkpoint sync messages |\\n   291→| `src/crons/reconciliation.ts` | Daily checkpoint reconciliation |\\n   292→| `migrations/0014_repo_centric_checkpoints.sql` | Schema migration to repo-centric tables |\\n   293→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"16b81c18-ae07-4c8f-ba1c-87